    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">A Study on Customer Relationship Management In Retail Banks with Reference To Kancheepuram District,Tamilnadu.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Vijayakumar.T</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Customer Relationship<br />Management in Retial Banks</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Apr-2011 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0024</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">India’s retail bank customers are presently left with unlimited choices of retail products and with ever increasing expectation. In this context, the bankers, to remain competitive, have to meet the expectations of the customers much better than the competing players in the market.
This scenario has made the bankers focus on Customer Relationship Management to treat customers as lifelong, profitable partners. This is possible for any bank, by improving and consistently performing to the changing needs of the customers. The CRM in retail banking throws open wide scope of analysis and this is an inducing element for the researcher to take up this profound study.
The factors of concern of this study are the, influences contributing to relationship building, sustaining relationship, and influences leading to dissolution of relationship. The service quality perception variables differ between the bank customers and the bank employees. A meaningful understanding of these variables would obviously contribute to measuring and arriving at relationship building strategies. Misunderstanding influences leads to inappropriate relationship strategies and this is the focal point of research in retail bank customer relationship building and the same is identified as the problem for study with the following objectives.
The broad objective of the study is to understand the CRM practices of retail banks and to critically analyze the perceived service quality of the customers and employees of retail banks in Kancheepuram district during the period 2006-11.
Based on the above stated broad objective, the specific objectives are:-
 To develop a frame work for CRM Model applicable to retail banks.
 To study external and internal services quality perception with respect to retail banks.
 To analyze the influences of service quality on customer behaviour with respect to retail banks.
 To identify the key variables that contributes to relationship building in order of their relative significance.
 To identify customer relationship strategies that can be adopted by the banks for better delivery of the services to their customers.
 To determine the customer satisfaction levels and their influence in building customer loyalty to achieve a sustained market share and profit.
The study is based on the survey conducted on the selected retail banks in Kanchipuram district. The selected banks are the ICICI bank, the CUB bank (Private Sector Banks), Indian bank, State Bank of India (Nationalized Bank), Barclay Bank and CITI Bank (Foreign Bank). The data for study have been collected through two different questionnaires. One questionnaire was administered to the customers and another questionnaire to the bank employees of six banks. A pilot study was conducted to ensure the accuracy and adquencey of data collection tools.
The research questions are aimed to understand the significant relationship between the various demography of the customer to their perception, expectation
and satisfaction towards the existing CRM system in the retail banks. This focuses on the external service quality parameters.
On the other hand the internal service quality parameters are assessed by the employee’s acceptance, influencing factors and effectiveness of the existing CRM practices in the retail banks.
The study brings to light the various aspects relating to relationship building in retail banking industry. The variable identified, which contribute to relationship building and dissolution of relationship, will definitely help bankers to evolve appropriate strategies towards relationship building. The study has also found that there has been a difference in the perception of service quality among the customer and bankers as regard to several aspects of relationship management. Such service quality perception gaps are to be minimized so that the bankers can gain advantage in the competitive environment. The relationship model identified in the study would throw further light on strategic decision pertaining to relationship building.
An effective Customer Relationship Management programme, designed and executed, will obviously provide a win-win platform to both the bankers and the stake-holder. The research study provides insights into the development of banking in India, with focus on retail banking; that would enable all concerned to have a clear understanding of Indian banking industry, both in retrospective and prospective perspectives. The study is built as a humble contribution to achieve this goal.</td></tr>
